{{distinguish|Ada Initiative}} {{Infobox school |image = Ada Developers Academy.svg |name = Ada Developers Academy |established = 2013 |type = [[Private school|Private]] |founders = Elise Worthy, Scott Case, Susannah Malarkey |city = [[Seattle, Washington]] |website = {{URL|https://adadevelopersacademy.org}} }}
'''Ada Developers Academy''' (Ada) is a year-long intensive school in [[software development]] for women and people of non-binary gender with no previous professional experience in [[computer programming]].<ref name="geekwire" /> The program is tuition-free, and students can apply for a low-interest microloan to meet living expenses during the year.
The program is divided into 6 months of classroom instruction and a 5-month paid internship with a Seattle tech company. The first six months in the classroom focuses on [[Ruby (programming language)|Ruby]], [[Ruby on Rails]], [[JavaScript]] (including [[AngularJS]]<ref name='geekwire'/>), [[HTML]] and [[CSS]], and [[computer science]] fundamentals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.xconomy.com/seattle/2014/09/24/ada-developers-academy-offers-women-a-way-into-tech-boom/ |title=Ada Developers Academy Offers Women a Way into Tech Boom |last=Romano |first=Benjamin |work=XConomy.com |date=24 September 2014 |accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref> The last five months is an [[internship]] placement.<ref name="ada-xconomy">{{Cite news|url=http://www.xconomy.com/seattle/2014/08/08/seattle-roundup-rover-tune-rhapsody-rightside-zillow-ada/ |title=Seattle Roundup: Rover, Tune, Rhapsody, Rightside, Zillow, Ada |last=Romano |first=Benjamin |work=XConomy.com |date=8 August 2014 |accessdate=31 August 2014}}</ref> Interns are placed at sponsor companies including Amazon, Chef, Concur, EMC² Isilon Storage Division, EnergySavvy, Expedia, Getty Images, Marchex, Microsoft, Moz, Nordstrom, Redfin, Tune, Substantial, Zillow, and more.
== Cohorts == In its first cohort, 2013-2014, Ada Developers Academy took on 16 students. All of the first cohort obtained full-time job offers in software development before the course ended, and two of them received job offers from [[Amazon.com]]. Salaries for the job offers the students received averaged $75,000.<ref name="geekwire" /> {| class="wikitable" !Cohort !Start Date !Applicants !Accepted |- |1 |2013 |107 |16 |- |2 |2014 |190 |24 |- |3 |May 2015 |206 |24 |- |4 |Sep 2015 |272 |24 |- |5 |Feb 2016 |306 |24 |- |6 |Aug 2016 |399 |48 |- |7 |Feb 2017 |356 |48 |- |8 |Aug 2017 |475 |TBD |}
== Funding == Ada began as a project of Seattle's [[Technology Alliance]] and is funded through company sponsorship, individual donors, and public sources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.dice.com/2013/09/26/free-software-developer-school-for-women-launches-in-seattle-056/ |title=Free Software Developer School for Women Launches |last=Grauer |first=Yael |website=Dice News |date=26 September 2013 |accessdate=5 October 2013}}</ref> Ada now operates as a nonprofit through its financial sponsor, [[Third Sector New England]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tsne.org/ada-developers-academy |title=Third Sector New England |website=TSNE |date=21 July 2015 |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> Ada's company sponsors include Amazon.com, [[Expedia]], [[Zillow]], and [[Chef (company)|Chef]]. Sponsors provide input into the course's curriculum, and mentoring and internships for the students. Sponsoring companies such as Expedia stated that they participate in the program in order to recruit great talent, and also in order to improve their [[Diversity (business)|diversity]].<ref name='geekwire'>{{Cite news|url=http://www.geekwire.com/2015/closing-gender-gap-ada-developers-academy-helps-women-learn-programming-skills-free/ |title=Closing the gender gap: Ada Developer's Academy helps women learn programming skills for free |last=Soper |first=Taylor |website=GeekWire |date=22 January 2015 |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>
