{{Infobox philosopher |era = [[20th-century philosophy]]/[[21st-century philosophy]], |image= AlanOlson.jpg |caption = |name = Alan M. Olson |birth_date = {{Birth date|1939|01|07|mf=y}} |birth_place = [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]], United States |death_date = |death_place = |region = [[Western philosophy]] |school_tradition = [[Continental philosophy]] |main_interests = [[Philosophy of Religion]], [[German Idealism]], [[Philosophical Theology]], [[Existentialism]], [[Phenomenology (philosophy)|Phenomenology]], [[Hermeneutics]] |notable_ideas = [[Karl Jaspers|Jaspers]] and Cross-cultural [[Hermeneutics]], [[Hegel]] and [[Pneumatology]] |influences = [[Karl Jaspers]], [[Hans-Georg Gadamer]], [[Paul Ricoeur]], [[John N. Findlay]] |influenced = }}
'''Alan M. Olson''' is a Professor of the Philosophy of Religion, Emeritus, at Boston University]]. He received his degrees from [[Saint Olaf College]] (BA, History and Philosophy), [[Luther Theological Seminary]] (MDiv, Theology), [[Nashotah House]], where he studied with [[Arthur Anton Vogel]], and Boston University (PhD) where he studied with [[Peter A. Bertocci]], [[Erazim Kohak]], [[Harold H. Oliver]] and [[John Niemeyer Findlay|John N. Findlay]]. He served as Chairman of the Religion Department at Boston University, 1980–1987, and Chairman of the Philosophy Department, ad interim, 1987-1989.<ref>Alan Olson, [http://www.bu.edu/religion/faculty/bios/olson/ Abbreviated Curriculum Vitae]</ref> During the 1970s he was Program Coordinator of the Boston University Institute for Philosophy and Religion; and was Executive Director of the [[World Congress of Philosophy|Twentieth World Congress of Philosophy]] in Boston, 1998. He was a Senior Fulbright Research Fellow at [[Universität Tübingen|Karls-Eberhart Universität]], Tübingen, Germany, in 1986, where he studied with [[Klaus Hartmann]]; and a Senior Fulbright Research Fellow and Visiting Fellow at the [[Institut für die Wissenschaften vom Menschen]], Vienna, Austria, in 1995, where he worked with [[Krzysztof Michalski]]. He served on the Board of Officers of the [[American Philosophical Association]], 2000–2003; and is past president of the [[Karl Jaspers Society of North America]]. He delivered the Jaspers Lectures at Oxford in 1989; and was co-editor, with [[Helmut Wautischer]], of the philosophical journal, [[Existenz (journal)|Existenz]] from 2006 to 2015. He lives on [[Cape Cod]] with his wife, [[Janet L. Olson]], Professor Emerita, College of Fine Arts, Boston University. They have two daughters, Maren Kirsten, Sonja Astrid, and one grandson, Søren.
==Books and Edited Works== *''Transcendence and Hermeneutics'' - {{ISBN|978-90-247-2092-7}} <ref>[https://www.springer.com/social+sciences/religious+studies/book/978-90-247-2092-7 Springer Verlag]</ref> *''The Seeing Eye'', Co-Author - {{ISBN|0-271-00291-3}} *''Hegel and the Spirit'' - {{ISBN|0-691-07411-9}} <ref>[http://press.princeton.edu/titles/5024.html Princeton University Press]</ref> *''Disguises of the Demonic'', Ed. - {{ISBN|0-8096-1896-6}} *''Myth, Symbol, and Reality'', Ed. - {{ISBN|0-268-01346-2}} <ref>[http://undpress.nd.edu/book/P00738 University of Notre Dame Press]</ref> *''Transcendence and the Sacred'', Co-Ed. - {{ISBN|0-268-01841-3}} *''Heidegger and Jaspers'', Ed. - {{ISBN|1-56639-115-6}} <ref>[http://www.temple.edu/tempress/titles/1019_reg.html Temple University Press]</ref> *''Video Icons & Values'', Co-Ed. - {{ISBN|0-7914-0412-9}} <ref>[http://www.sunypress.edu/p-994-video-icons-values.aspx State University of New York Press]</ref> *''Educating for Democracy'', Co-Ed. - {{ISBN|0-7425-3540-1}} *''Proceedings of the Twentieth World Congress of Philosophy, 12 Vols.'', Exec. Ed. - {{ISBN|1-889680-19-2}} *''Philosophical Faith and the Future of Humanity, Co-Ed, - {{ISBN|978-94-007-2222-4}} <ref>[https://www.springer.com/social+sciences/applied+ethics/book/978-94-007-2222-4 Springer Verlag]</ref>
